lysis, the introduction deals with Lucillius’s identity, the tradition of the text, style, themes, metrics, and cultural setting, and additionally investigates the origins and development of Greek skoptic epigram. Particular attention is paid to the way in which Lucillius engages with the conventions of the genre, often overturning the reader’s expectations. In this way, the work explores the paradox inherent to the fact that a poetic form that was by its nature eulogistic (inscriptional epigrams were born in order to record, and thus celebrate, the dedication of an object or the death of a man) ultimately became the genre of mockery and abuse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Italian.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEpigrams, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aEpigrams, GreekxTranslations into Italian. 0aEpigrams, Greek. 0aEpigrams, Latin. 0aGriechische Literatur. 4aAnthologia Graeca. 4aLucillius. 4aSkoptisches Epigramm. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aGreek satire.  aLucillius.  askoptic epigram.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2014z9783110369618oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG0 cEPUBz97831103827610 cprintz978311033616040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311033650440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110336504423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110336504/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2014  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-GCNc2000d2014